<setup>
  <piecewiseFunction name="f" styleNumber="1">
    <function domain="(-4,-2)">(2*(x+2.5))^3-2</function>
    <function domain="(-2,0)">-0.5*(x+2)-1</function>
    <function domain="(0,1.5)">-4*(x-1)^2 + 2</function>
    <function domain="(1.5,4)">-1*(x-1.5)^2+1</function>  
  </piecewiseFunction>


</setup>  

<p>
  Consider the function <m>y = h(x)</m> defined by the following graph.  Assume that the domain of <m>h</m> is <m>[-3,3]</m>.
</p>  

      <graph xmin="-3" xmax="3" ymin="-3" ymax="3" size="medium" grid="true" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true"> 
        $f  
        <label fixLocation anchor="(1.1,2.1)"><m>h</m></label>
      </graph>

  <p>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify all of the values of <m>c</m> such that <m>-3 \lt c \lt 3</m> for which <m>h(c)</m> is a local maximum of <m>h</m>.  If more than one, separate your values with commas; if there are none, enter <em>none</em>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        <m>c = </m>
        <answer unorderedCompare matchPartial>
          <mathList>-2 1</mathList>
        </answer>
      </p>
        
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify all of the values of <m>c</m> such that <m>-3 \lt c \lt 3</m> for which <m>h(c)</m> is a local minimum of <m>h</m>. If more than one, separate your values with commas; if there are none, enter <em>none</em>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        <m>c = </m>
        <answer>
          0
        </answer>
      </p>

      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>h</m> has a global maximum on the interval <m>[-3,3]</m>, enter the value of the global maximum.  If <m>h</m> doesn't have a global maximum, enter <em>none</em>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        The global maximum of the function <m>h</m> is
        <answer>
          2
        </answer>
      </p>

      
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>h</m> has a global minimum on the interval <m>[-3,3]</m>, enter the value of the global minimum.  If <m>h</m> doesn't have a global minimum, enter <em>none</em>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        The global minimum of the function <m>h</m> is
        <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute>
          -3
        </answer>
      </p>
      
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify all values of <m>c</m> for which <m>h'(c) = 0</m>; if there is more than one, separate your values with commas.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        <m>c = </m>
          <answer unorderedCompare  allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute matchPartial>
            <mathList>-2.5 1</mathList>
          </answer>
      </p>
      
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify all values of <m>c</m> for which <m>h'(c)</m> does not exist; if there is more than one, separate your values with commas.
        </p>
      </li>

            
      <p>
        <m>c = </m>
          <answer unorderedCompare  allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute matchPartial>
            <mathList>-2 0 1.5</mathList>
          </answer>
      </p>
      
      <li>
        <p>
          True or false:
          every relative maximum and minimum of <m>h</m> occurs at a point where <m>h'(c)</m> is either zero or does not exist.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        <answer>
          <choiceInput inLine="true">
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice credit="1">True</choice>
            <choice>False</choice>
          </choiceInput>
        </answer>
      </p>

      <li>
        <p>
          True or false:
          at every point where <m>h'(c)</m> is zero or does not exist,
          <m>h</m> has a relative maximum or minimum.
        </p>
      </li>

      <p>
        <answer>
          <choiceInput inLine="true">
            <choice>True</choice>
            <choice credit="1">False</choice>
          </choiceInput>
        </answer>
      </p>
      
    </ol>
  </p>
<!-- </exploration> -->